* 1/21/22 PLTR $40 3x Call Buy

Today was a great day for discounted stock. I loaded up on T calls, doubled down on PLTR and APHA on the dips, and cautiously diversified into superconductors to see if y'all fuck that up too. Tomorrow I will be eyeing my options and seeing how I aggressively I want to play T.

On all the "short term" stocks, I have sell orders once it hits 25% profit to sell most of my position. GME burnt me. I took out the SNDL and APHA LEAPS before I understand how devastating IV can be, so hopefully I can average those down. They're still good strike prices. If APHA stops running for a bit, I'll buy more of that too.

author: clown-penisdotfart
body:
I'm throwing money at semiconductors now. If anything the entire industry is undervalued. Semis are the linchpin of society. They are everywhere and will only grow in application space. More Moore is where it's at. But don't think of just the manufacturers (though I agree Intel will pop huge once they get their shit together or spin out manufacturing, either way), don't forget the suppliers to the manufacturers like Applied Materials, Lam Research, ASML, etc. Whether it be TSMC, Samsung, Intel, Micron, SK Hynix, or any other manufacturer or fabless company doing well, those companies win big. 

I hold a lot of $SOXX because of this.

author: aaj15
body: LRCX, AMAT, KLA, ASML, ENTG, BRKS, ASMIY. These are some I could think of that have stocks in the US. There are a lot of japanese/taiwanese companies that provide raw materials but not available in the US stock exchanges. From what I understand GLW makes polysilicon which isn't what used for making transistors..in any case, silicon isn't what is causing the bottleneck. It's the ABF (someone mentioned this already above) and just lack  capacity to make more chips..which is why tsmc and samsung announced earlier this year significant investment in capacity expansion

author: MysteryPerker
body:
Oh I'm just interested in tech like semiconductors anyways and I'm new to investing and missed the rise. I remember watching AMD's recent CPU release and the Nvidia 3000 series release and they were talking about new semiconductors coming out that in 5 nm soon, as well as coming closer to getting 3 nm. But it's a time consuming process to build these chips. It costs billions to build new facilities, and takes a few months. They are in the process of expanding current production because literally everything uses them. Car manufacturers can't make new cars because they can't get chips to put in them. GPU shortages because they can't get chips. Console shortages due to chips not available. Most semiconductor companies have production already to the max through 2022. TSM is a good company. It is the defacto #1 worldwide producer and industry leader in semiconductors. Samsung is #2. There are smaller companies I've been diving into as well. AMD Zen 4 CPUs sound amazing. But I honestly suggest getting into something that interests you naturally and do DD on them. I was doing DD by just keeping up with leaks like the one below. Should have started investing last summer instead of just getting excited about new releases lol. But I hate giving advice when I am quite literally a novice at this. You could also look at semiconductor ETFs if you don't want to just pick one. 

I'm currently looking at TSM, AMAT (they make semiconductor foundry parts), UMC, MU, LSCC. And I'm keeping an eye on AMD for their Zen 4 release next year. It should also support DDR5 RAM, which is twice as fast as DDR4, and PCI.e5 too. But yeah, I love keeping up with this market and I have tried to get into DD for industries I'm not so interested in and it always flopped. I did buy POWW, an ammunition manufacturer, just because my dad talks about ammo shortages all the time. It's done well the last few weeks and I anticipate it will continue that route until earnings are reported on February 16th. I do not plan on keeping it long though, as I believe having a Democrat president is contributing to the shortages. So just keep stocks in mind whenever you learn about shit and do some DD on those things. 

Not financial advice, blah blah blah, I'm an idiot and also lose money haha. I also am only playing around with $1.5K so I just have handfuls of each one and it's not a big deal if it's lost.

author: BallsForBears
body:
ON - U.S. chip production. Play on whitehouse intervening in shortage.

UMC - Small cap manufacturer, plenty of room to grow during this shortage.

AMAT - Long-term play, they provide services, materials, and equipment for the chip manufacturing chain.

TSM - Large cap company but dominant in the market, they are also opening a japan plant this year to increase production.

I don’t think there are any wrong plays you can make here as long as you target B2B in the chain.
